eevaluated, and new relationships—often more egalitarian—emerge. Women gain greater personal autonomy and independence as they participate in public life and gain access to both social and economic influence previously beyond their reach.Bringing to life the experiences of undocumented immigrants and delineating the key role of women in newly established communities, Gendered Transitions challenges conventional assumptions about gender and migration. It will be essential reading for demographers, historians, sociologists, and policymakers."I've opened my eyes. Back there, they say 'no.' You marry, and no, you must stay home. Here, it's different. You marry, and you continue working. Back in Mexico, it's very different. There is very much machismo in those men."—A Mexican woman living in the United States  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMexicanszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aWomen immigrantszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aamerican history.  acommunity.  ademographics.  adomestic.  aegalitarian.  afamily life.  agender roles.  aimmigrant experience.  aimmigration.  alabor law.  alabor policy.  alabor.  alifestyle.  amexican immigrants.  amexican.  amexico.  amigrant workers.  amigration.  apolicymakers.  asettlement.  asocial justice.  asociology.  astarting over.  aundocumented workers.  aus history.  awomens issues.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091152940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520911529423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520911529/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aG